Comments :
Carl Brashear, born in 1931 to sharecroppers, joins the Navy and, after watching the 
heroics of Billy Sunday, the White son of a sharecropper, determines to become the 
Navy&#039;s first African-American diver. At the Bayonne, N.J., divers&#039; training camp, 
Sunday is his instructor, and Brasher must endure hazing verging on the murderous. 
With Sunday and the camp&#039;s commander dead set against Brashear&#039;s graduating, his 
physical skills and steely determination, which he got from his father, see him through. 
Carl and Billy&#039;s paths cross again when each needs rehabilitation one from an injury, 
the other from bitterness. Their wives look on with awe and frustration.
